		<td><b>about Brad Taylor's ref</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />In Brad Taylor's ref, he said:"the PPU fetches an attribute table byte for every 8 sequential horizontal pixels it draws."
<br />
<br />why 8? i think it should be 32 because one attribute table byte contain all the high 2 bit for a 4*4 tiles group. help me please.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Quietust</b> [ Thu Jan 26, 2006 10:19 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It is true that one set of attribute bits applies to 4 tiles at once, but the PPU has no such buffers inside it - as such, it will re-fetch the same attribute bytes for <strong>all</strong> of the appropriate tiles.
<br />
<br />The upside to this is that it makes the MMC5's "extended attribute" mode possible (which uses extra RAM to allow setting <em>per-tile</em> attribute data).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


